<text>
    <group>
       
    
    <!-- type is letter -->

    
        
        <pb n="5383" facs="#L1916_2123_img_5383"/>
            <text type="letter" decls="#corresp1">
                <body>
                    

<opener><address><addrLine>"Ardeevin"</addrLine></address>
<dateline><date>March 30th</date></dateline>
<salute>Dearest Mamma</salute></opener>
<p> I do hope poor Emma<lb/>
 has returned home! I have been thinking<lb/>
 &amp; worrying about her being <unclear>showered</unclear> <lb/>
and she would feel the cold so.</p>
<p>We had a great meeting together<lb/> 
but she will tell you all that<lb/> 
&amp; about our visit to the Admiralty.</p>
<p>I hope I've done the right thing.<lb/> 
I don't know. But any way I am not<lb/> 
bound to anything. I dread the start.<lb/>
I wish I could have had my visit<lb/> 
to Eastbourne &amp; <unclear>Winchester</unclear> first.</p>
<p>I have found rooms (for a time anyway)<lb/>
 by a strange chance at <lb/>
152 Vauxhall Bishope Road London</p> 
<p>I went to enquire at Alexandria<lb/>
 Ladies Club, Grosvenor St about rooms,<lb/>
quite a smart place. Not II feel<lb/>
sure the place I intended. I saw
        
    

    
         
        <pb n="5384" facs="#L1916_2123_img_5384"/>
        
        
           
            the Secretary who was pleasant and<lb/>
 said she had a friend upstairs who<lb/>
 might keep me. Down came a Mrs<lb/>
R ONeill, widow of a Colonel R ONeill,<lb/>
who said she was now living &amp; working<lb/>
at the Club but she had left<lb/>
a friend, Miss Holmes at her<lb/>
flat &amp; this friend was anxious<lb/>
to find paying guests so as not have<lb/>
to give it up. Already a girl<lb/> 
working at the Admiralty is there<lb/>
&amp; one or two other ladies. After<lb/>
much chat we came to terms ( I<lb/>
think I must have looked pathetically<lb/> 
tired!) She said I will lodge<lb/>
at the flat for a guinea a week<lb/>
 &amp; have breakfast &amp; dinner there,<lb/> 
(also lunch on Sundays) bath, light<lb/>
 and <unclear>attendance.</unclear></p>
<p>Her friend (Miss Holmes) was coming<lb/>
to tea with her at the Club, <unclear>and</unclear><lb/>
she gave me a note to the maid<lb/>
&amp; I went off &amp; saw the place. It
        
    
         
        <pb n="5385" facs="#L1916_2123_img_5385"/>
        
        
           
            is near  Victoria station &amp; convenient to<lb/>
 Whitehall - quite a pleasant house,<lb/>
with a nice drawing room, flowers<lb/>
and bright fire, quite nice bedrooms<lb/> 
&amp; a cheerful maid.<lb/>
Well &#x2014; I've heard from Miss Holmes,<lb/>
&amp; I go there on Saturday. I shall<lb/> 
lunch with the <unclear>MacLeods</unclear> &amp; probably <lb/>
meet Celia in the evening, &amp; start<lb/>
work on Monday. It seems a<lb/> 
promising venture but I doubt if<lb/>
she'll keep me long on those terms.<lb/>
26/&#x2014; was asked even so with<lb/>
washing, lunching out etc, I calculate<lb/> 
I shall be losing at least 10/&#x2014; a week! If there is<lb/>
 no rise I can't stay at the Admiralty<lb/> 
&#x2014; however they may <unclear>chuck</unclear> me! </p> 
<p> I interviewed a Secretary at the new<lb/>
War office place &#x2014;
 the pay and hours were<lb/>
better there but no immediate<lb/>
vacancy. The Secretary said I<pb/>
        
    
         
        <pb n="5386" facs="#L1916_2123_img_5386"/>
        
        
           
            should do much better </p>
<p>I'm sure you are delighted to<lb/>
 have Emma. I feel I did not <lb/>
half see her - everything was so<lb/>rushed</p>
<p>I've been all over London lately <lb/> 
between looking for jobs &amp; lodgings.<lb/>
Bedford House was quite full<lb/>
up.</p>
<p>Annie <unclear>Hollins</unclear> turned up here last<lb/>
night 6 hours late because of <lb/>
the snow which make me fear for<lb/>
Emma. She has been babbling<lb/>
ever since!</p>
<p>I trust that now you will come over in <lb/>
May &amp; see me &amp; Annie F.</p>
<p>Best love Dear- I won't have<lb/>
much time for letters when I start<lb/>
work!</p>
<closer><salute>Your loving</salute>
<signed> Dussie</signed></closer>
<note>Best love to Papa.<lb/>
I hope he keeps well.<lb/>
I didn't expect to be away so long when<lb/>
I left home!</note>
        
    
                </body>
